3.0 FOUNDATIONS: NETWORK THEORY OF ECONOMIC METABOLISM

3.0.1 The Economic Stoichiometric Matrix - Advanced Construction

Definition 3.0.1 (Extended Economic Stoichiometric Space):
For each economic metabolite i, define its value state v_i \in \mathbb{R}^d (d-dimensional feature vector: liquidity, volatility, utility, etc.). The stoichiometric tensor becomes:

S \in \mathbb{Z}^{m \times n \times d}


with

S_{ijk} = \text{change in feature } k \text{ of metabolite } i \text{ in reaction } j

Dynamic Tensor Balance:

\frac{d\mathbf{X}}{dt} = \mathbf{S} \times_3 \mathbf{V} - \mathbf{B}


Where:

· \mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times d}: metabolite feature matrix
· \mathbf{V} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times t}: reaction flux matrix over time
· \times_3: tensor mode-3 product
· \mathbf{B} \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times d}: external feature supply/demand

3.0.2 Economic Reaction Kinetics with Information-Theoretic Costs

Extended Michaelis-Menten with Information Processing:

v_j = \frac{V_{\max,j} e^{-I_j/k_B T_{info}} \prod_{i \in S} \frac{x_i}{K_{M,ij} + x_i}}{1 + \sum_{k \in I} \frac{x_k}{K_{I,kj}} + \sum_{l \in C} \frac{x_l^h}{K_{C,lj}^h + x_l^h}}

Where I_j is the information processing cost of reaction j:

I_j = \sum_{i=1}^m |S_{ij}| \cdot H(p_i) \cdot \log_2(1 + \frac{1}{\text{SNR}_{ij}})


H(p_i) = entropy of metabolite i's distribution, SNR = signal-to-noise ratio.

Economic Allosteric Regulation with Multiple Modulators:

v_j = V_{\max,j} \cdot \frac{[S]}{K_M + [S]} \cdot \prod_{a \in \text{activators}} \frac{1 + \alpha_a [A_a]/K_a}{1 + [A_a]/K_a} \cdot \prod_{i \in \text{inhibitors}} \frac{1}{1 + [I_i]/K_i}

