3.1 GENOME-SCALE METABOLIC MODELING (GEM) OF ECONOMIC SYSTEMS

3.1.1 Constraint-Based Reconstruction with Multi-Objective Optimization

Multi-Objective FBA (MO-FBA):

\begin{aligned}
\text{Pareto front: } & \max_{\mathbf{v}} \{\mathbf{c}_1^T\mathbf{v}, \mathbf{c}_2^T\mathbf{v}, \ldots, \mathbf{c}_k^T\mathbf{v}\} \\
\text{s.t. } & S\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{b} \\
& \mathbf{v}_{\min} \leq \mathbf{v} \leq \mathbf{v}_{\max}
\end{aligned}

Solution via ε-Constraint Method:
Fix one objective, convert others to constraints:

\begin{aligned}
\max_{\mathbf{v}} & \quad \mathbf{c}_1^T\mathbf{v} \\
\text{s.t. } & \quad \mathbf{c}_j^T\mathbf{v} \geq \epsilon_j, \quad j=2,\ldots,k \\
& \quad S\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{b} \\
& \quad \mathbf{v}_{\min} \leq \mathbf{v} \leq \mathbf{v}_{\max}
\end{aligned}

Weighted Sum Method:

\max_{\mathbf{v}} \quad \sum_{i=1}^k w_i \mathbf{c}_i^T\mathbf{v}


with w_i \geq 0, \sum w_i = 1.

3.1.2 Dynamic FBA with Optimal Control Theory

Time-Dependent FBA:

\begin{aligned}
\max_{\mathbf{v}(t)} & \quad \int_0^T \mathbf{c}(t)^T\mathbf{v}(t) dt \\
\text{s.t. } & \quad \frac{d\mathbf{x}}{dt} = S\mathbf{v}(t) - \mathbf{b}(t) \\
& \quad \mathbf{x}(t) \geq 0 \\
& \quad \mathbf{v}_{\min} \leq \mathbf{v}(t) \leq \mathbf{v}_{\max}
\end{aligned}

Discretization and Linear Programming:
Divide [0,T] into N intervals:

\mathbf{x}^{k+1} = \mathbf{x}^k + \Delta t (S\mathbf{v}^k - \mathbf{b}^k)


Solve LP sequence with state constraints.

3.1.3 Metabolite-Centric FBA (MC-FBA)

Instead of maximizing flux through biomass, maximize metabolite production rate:

\max_{\mathbf{v}} \quad \sum_{i \in \mathcal{P}} w_i v_{prod,i}


Subject to stoichiometric and capacity constraints.

Shadow Price Analysis:
Dual variables \lambda_i for metabolite balance constraints represent marginal value:

\lambda_i = \frac{\partial Z^*}{\partial b_i}


Where Z^* is optimal objective value.

Reduced Cost Analysis:

r_j = c_j - \lambda^T S_{\cdot j}


Where S_{\cdot j} = j-th column of S. If r_j < 0 for non-basic variable, including reaction j could improve objective.

3.1.4 Geometric Algorithms for Flux Cone Analysis

Double Description Method for Large Networks:

Algorithm 3.1.1 (DDM for Economic Networks):

1. Initialize with matrix A representing constraints: A\mathbf{v} \leq 0
2. Represent cone as intersection of halfspaces (H-representation)
3. Convert to extreme rays (V-representation)
4. Incrementally add constraints, updating extreme rays

For system S\mathbf{v} = 0, \mathbf{v} \geq 0:
Initial rays: R_0 = \{\mathbf{e}_1, \ldots, \mathbf{e}_n\} (standard basis)
For each constraint a_i^T\mathbf{v} = 0:

· Partition rays into R^+, R^0, R^- based on sign of a_i^T\mathbf{r}
· Generate new rays: \mathbf{r}_{new} = (a_i^T\mathbf{r}^-)\mathbf{r}^+ - (a_i^T\mathbf{r}^+)\mathbf{r}^-
· Remove redundant rays

Complexity: O(n^2) rays in worst case, but typically O(n) for metabolic networks.

3.1.5 Thermodynamic Driving Force Analysis

Gibbs Free Energy of Economic Reactions:

\Delta_r G_j' = \Delta_r G_j'^\circ + RT \sum_i S_{ij} \ln(x_i) + \text{correction terms}

Economic Potential Landscape:
Define economic potential \mu_i for metabolite i:

\mu_i = \mu_i^0 + k_B T \ln(x_i) + z_i \phi + \text{non-ideal terms}


Where \phi = economic "electric potential" (market sentiment).

Flux-Force Relationship (Onsager):

v_j = L_{jj} \frac{-\Delta_r G_j'}{RT} + \sum_{k \neq j} L_{jk} \frac{-\Delta_r G_k'}{RT}


With Onsager reciprocal relations: L_{jk} = L_{kj}.

Metabolic Control Analysis (MCA) for Economics:

Elasticity Coefficients:

\epsilon_i^j = \frac{\partial \ln v_j}{\partial \ln x_i}

Control Coefficients:

C_i^j = \frac{\partial \ln J}{\partial \ln E_i}


Where J = system flux, E_i = enzyme concentration (economic catalyst).

Summation Theorem:

\sum_i C_i^J = 1

Connectivity Theorem:

\sum_j C_i^J \epsilon_k^j = 0

