3.2 REGULATORY NETWORK INFERENCE WITH DEEP LEARNING

3.2.1 Neural Network Representations of Boolean Functions

Let f: \{0,1\}^n \to \{0,1\} be a Boolean update function.

Representation Theorem: Any Boolean function can be represented as:

f(\mathbf{x}) = \text{sign}\left(\sum_{S \subseteq [n]} w_S \prod_{i \in S} x_i\right)

Minimal Network Construction:
Use Quine-McCluskey algorithm to find minimal DNF/CNF.

Probabilistic Boolean Networks (PBNs):
Each gene has multiple possible update functions with probabilities:

P(f_i^{(j)} \text{ selected}) = c_i^{(j)}, \quad \sum_j c_i^{(j)} = 1

Dynamic Bayesian Networks (DBNs):

P(\mathbf{x}(t+1)|\mathbf{x}(t)) = \prod_{i=1}^n P(x_i(t+1)|\text{Pa}_i(\mathbf{x}(t)))

Learning DBNs with Regularization:

\max_{\theta} \quad \log P(\mathcal{D}|\theta) - \lambda_1 \|\theta\|_1 - \lambda_2 \text{TV}(\theta)


Where TV = total variation penalty for smoothness.

3.2.2 Causal Structure Learning with Interventions

do-Calculus Rules (Pearl):

1. Insertion/deletion of observations
2. Action/observation exchange
3. Insertion/deletion of actions

Causal Discovery with Instrumental Variables:
For system: Y = \alpha X + \epsilon, find Z such that:

· Z correlates with X
· Z affects Y only through X
· Z is independent of ε

Two-Stage Least Squares:
Stage 1: X = \pi Z + \nu
Stage 2: Y = \alpha \hat{X} + \epsilon

3.2.3 ODE Networks with Sparse Identification (SINDy)

Sparse Identification of Nonlinear Dynamics:
Given data \{\mathbf{x}(t), \dot{\mathbf{x}}(t)\}, construct library \Theta(\mathbf{x}) = [1, \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}^{\otimes 2}, \ldots, \mathbf{x}^{\otimes p}]

Solve:

\min_{\Xi} \quad \|\dot{\mathbf{X}} - \Theta(\mathbf{X})\Xi\|_2^2 + \lambda \|\Xi\|_1

Where \Xi is sparse coefficient matrix.

Extended SINDy for Economic Networks:
Include cross terms, rational functions, and delay terms:

\Theta(\mathbf{x}) = [1, \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}^{\otimes 2}, \frac{1}{1+\mathbf{x}}, \frac{\mathbf{x}_i}{\mathbf{x}_j}, \mathbf{x}(t-\tau)]

