3.5 MULTI-OMICS INTEGRATION WITH TENSOR DECOMPOSITION

3.5.1 Tensor Decomposition Methods

CP Decomposition:

\mathcal{X} \approx \sum_{r=1}^R \lambda_r \mathbf{a}_r \circ \mathbf{b}_r \circ \mathbf{c}_r


Where \circ = outer product.

Tucker Decomposition:

\mathcal{X} \approx \mathcal{G} \times_1 A \times_2 B \times_3 C


Where \mathcal{G} = core tensor.

Block Term Decomposition (BTD):

\mathcal{X} \approx \sum_{r=1}^R (\mathcal{G}_r \times_1 A_r \times_2 B_r \times_3 C_r)

3.5.2 Joint Non-Negative Matrix Factorization (jNMF)

For K data matrices X^{(k)} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times p_k}:

\min_{W, H^{(k)}} \quad \sum_{k=1}^K \|X^{(k)} - WH^{(k)}\|_F^2 + \lambda \|W\|_1 + \sum_k \mu_k \|H^{(k)}\|_1


Subject to W \geq 0, H^{(k)} \geq 0.

Shared factor matrix W captures common structure.

3.5.3 Multi-Omics Manifold Alignment

Given datasets X^{(k)} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times d_k}, find embeddings Y^{(k)} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times r} preserving within-omics structure and aligning across omics.

Objective:

\min_{Y^{(k)}} \quad \sum_k \text{tr}(Y^{(k)} L^{(k)} Y^{(k)T}) + \lambda \sum_{k<l} \|Y^{(k)} - Y^{(l)}\|_F^2


Where L^{(k)} = Laplacian of k-th omics similarity graph.

Solution via generalized eigenvalue problem.

---

3.6 DIGITAL TWIN WITH REAL-TIME ADAPTATION

3.6.1 Ensemble Kalman Filter with Localization

Standard EnKF:

\mathbf{x}^a = \mathbf{x}^f + K(\mathbf{y} - H\mathbf{x}^f)



K = P^f H^T (HP^f H^T + R)^{-1}

Covariance Localization:
Multiply sample covariance P^f with localization function:

P^f_{\text{localized}} = C \circ P^f


Where C_{ij} = \exp(-d_{ij}^2/2L^2) for distance d_{ij}, length scale L.

Inflation:

\mathbf{x}^f \leftarrow \alpha (\mathbf{x}^f - \bar{\mathbf{x}}^f) + \bar{\mathbf{x}}^f


with \alpha > 1 to prevent filter divergence.

3.6.2 Particle Filter with Adaptive Proposals

Sequential Importance Resampling (SIR):
Weight update:

w_t^{(i)} \propto w_{t-1}^{(i)} \frac{p(\mathbf{y}_t|\mathbf{x}_t^{(i)}) p(\mathbf{x}_t^{(i)}|\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^{(i)})}{q(\mathbf{x}_t^{(i)}|\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^{(i)}, \mathbf{y}_t)}

Optimal Proposal:

q_{\text{opt}}(\mathbf{x}_t|\mathbf{x}_{t-1}, \mathbf{y}_t) = p(\mathbf{x}_t|\mathbf{x}_{t-1}, \mathbf{y}_t)

Adaptive Resampling: Resample when effective sample size N_{\text{eff}} = 1/\sum_i (w_i)^2 < N/2.

3.6.3 Dynamic Model Averaging for Structural Uncertainty

Multiple models M_k with weights \pi_t^{(k)}:

Update via Bayesian model averaging:

\pi_t^{(k)} \propto \pi_{t-1}^{(k)} p(\mathbf{y}_t|M_k, \mathbf{y}_{1:t-1})

Model evidence:

p(\mathbf{y}_t|M_k, \mathbf{y}_{1:t-1}) = \int p(\mathbf{y}_t|\theta_k, M_k) p(\theta_k|M_k, \mathbf{y}_{1:t-1}) d\theta_k

Approximate via Laplace approximation or particle filter.

