3.9 CASE STUDY: GLOBAL SUPPLY CHAIN NETWORK

3.9.1 Multi-Layer Supply Chain Representation

Layers:

1. Physical flow layer: Goods movement
2. Financial flow layer: Payments
3. Information layer: Orders, forecasts
4. Control layer: Ownership, contracts

Inter-layer dependencies:

· Financial flow follows physical flow with delay
· Information flow precedes physical flow
· Control layer influences all others

3.9.2 Shock Propagation Model

Linear propagation:

\mathbf{x}_{t+1} = (I + A) \mathbf{x}_t + \mathbf{s}_t


Where \mathbf{x}_t = shock magnitude at nodes, A = adjacency, \mathbf{s}_t = external shocks.

Nonlinear saturation:

x_i(t+1) = \min\left(1, x_i(t) + \sum_j a_{ij} f(x_j(t))\right)


Where f(x) = x/(1+x) (saturation function).

Cascading failures:
Node i fails if load L_i > C_i (capacity). Failed node redistributes load to neighbors.

3.9.3 Resilience Metrics

Spectral radius \rho(A): Determines stability of linear system.

Algebraic connectivity \lambda_2 (Fiedler value): Measures how well-connected graph is.

Effective graph resistance R_{\text{eff}}:

R_{\text{eff}} = \sum_{i<j} r_{ij}


Where r_{ij} = resistance between i,j in electrical analogy.

Mean first passage time for random walk:

m_{ij} = 1 + \sum_{k \neq j} p_{ik} m_{kj}

---

3.10 VALIDATION FRAMEWORK

3.10.1 Cross-Validation for Network Models

k-Fold cross-validation for edges:
Mask fraction of edges, predict them from model.

AUC-ROC for link prediction:

\text{AUC} = \frac{1}{|E^+| \cdot |E^-|} \sum_{e^+ \in E^+} \sum_{e^- \in E^-} \mathbb{I}(s(e^+) > s(e^-))


Where s(e) = predicted score for edge e.

Precision@k:

P@k = \frac{\text{relevant edges in top k}}{\text{k}}

3.10.2 Model Comparison via Information Criteria

Akaike Information Criterion (AIC):

\text{AIC} = 2k - 2\ln(\hat{L})

Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC):

\text{BIC} = k\ln(n) - 2\ln(\hat{L})

Watanabe-Akaike Information Criterion (WAIC):

\text{WAIC} = -2\left(\text{lppd} - \sum_{i=1}^n \text{Var}_{\text{post}}(\ln p(y_i|\theta))\right)


Where lppd = log pointwise predictive density.

3.10.3 Out-of-Sample Prediction Error

Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):

\text{MAPE} = \frac{100\%}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left|\frac{y_i - \hat{y}_i}{y_i}\right|

Mean Squared Error (MSE):

\text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2

Diebold-Mariano test for comparing forecasts:
Test statistic:

DM = \frac{\bar{d}}{\sqrt{\hat{\sigma}_d^2/n}} \sim N(0,1)


Where d_i = e_{1i}^2 - e_{2i}^2 (difference in squared errors).

